Date: Tue 11 Mar 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Australian Broadcasting Company, Tue 11 Mar 2003 [edited]
<http://abc.net.au/news/newsitems/s803685.htm>

Australia: 16 Cairns residents test positive for dengue fever
-------------------------------------------------------------
Health authorities in the far north of Queensland say that they have
confirmed two more cases of the potentially fatal dengue fever and have
another 60 possible cases on file. Queensland Health says 16 Cairns
residents have so far tested positive for the mosquitoborne disease during
the past two weeks. Tropical Public Health Unit director Jeffrey Hanna says
the situation is similar to the "outbreak" in 1998, which afflicted about
500 people, 100 of whom required hospital treatment.
******
[3]
Date: Thu 13 Mar 2003
From: "Pablo Nart" <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: The Age, Wed 12 March 2003
<http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/03/12/1047431091016.html>

Australia: concern about dengue hemorrhagic fever risk in Cairns suburbs
------------------------------------------------------------------------
North Queensland health authorities are working frantically to contain an
outbreak of dengue fever spreading like wildfire through Cairns. Confirmed
cases of the tropical mosquitoborne disease almost doubled to 30, and at
least 30 other cases are suspected, the Tropical Public Health Unit stated.
Of major concern is that people infected by a different strain [serotype?]
in a 1998 outbreak will be infected again, leaving them vulnerable to the
potentially fatal dengue hemorrhagic fever. The health unit's public health
physician Geoffrey Hanna said the current outbreak was confined to 2 Cairns
suburbs that were also badly affected five years ago. Efforts were focused
on stopping the disease spreading further afield.
"That's one of our major concerns - is it going to jump to another suburb,
is it going to jump to Townsville?" Dr Hanna said. "I think it's inevitable
we will have some spread. But the question is when and how extensive will
it be? We just can't predict that." The worst-case scenario would be if the
disease spread to Port Douglas and Mossman, about 70 km north of Cairns,
where 274 people contracted the disease in the 1998 outbreak.
In a bid to contain the outbreak, authorities are interviewing each patient
about where they have been and who they have had contact with. Response
teams then go to those areas, eliminating mosquito sites, spraying suspect
spots, and warning households. Residents and tourists have been urged to
wear repellent and use mosquito coils. Those already sick have been told to
stay home.
******
[4]
Date: Thu 13 Mar 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News.com.au, Thu 13 Mar 2003 [edited]
<http://www.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,4057,6121247%255E1702,00.html>

Australia: dengue fever cases in Cairns continue to increase
------------------------------------------------------------
Tropical Public Health Unit (TPHU) spokeswoman Rose Spencer today said that
more than 40 people have been diagnosed with the mosquitoborne disease in
the far north Queensland tourist city of Cairns. Another 40 people are
awaiting the results of tests. Ms Spencer stated that cases had been
confirmed in the city's northern beaches, including Palm Cove, indicating
that the disease had spread from the inner city. The Dengue Response Team
is trying to ensure the outbreak does not spread beyond the city by
inspecting and spraying households.
Dengue mosquitoes breed in backyards and are active during the day.
Households are being urged to empty any stagnant water containers. A Cairns
City Council spokesman said if people fail to heed official warnings to
clean up their backyards, they could be punished. "The state government can
impose fines or (the resident) can end up in court, so it's quite essential
that people take those directions seriously," he said.
The authorities fear 500 Cairns and Port Douglas residents who were
infected by a different dengue strain [serotype] in a 1998 outbreak could
be infected again. The second infection would leave them vulnerable to
[developing] potentially fatal dengue hemorrhagic fever. There are about 50
million to 100 million cases of dengue fever worldwide each year and
several hundred thousand cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever.
(byline: Jordan Baker)
