[5]
Date: Tue 11 Mar 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Jakarta Post, Tue 11 Mar 2003 [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/detailnational.asp?fileid=20030311.D02&irec=3>

Indonesia: West Java set for worst outbreak of dengue fever
-----------------------------------------------------------
An outbreak of dengue fever claimed 19 lives in West Java in the month of
January [2003] alone, a health official in the provincial capital of
Bandung stated. The toll was compiled from 24 regencies and municipalities
in West Java, said Fatima Resmiyati, head of West Java's Health Office
Environmental Bureau. She said the death toll was almost certainly higher
than 19, as her office continued to seek data in the months after January.
Her office has recorded 417 cases of dengue fever.
Its spread had reached worrying levels, Fatima said, adding that the
regencies of Subang, Depok, Indramayu, and Cirebon had registered 12
deaths. She said the last outbreak, following a five-year cycle, occurred
in 1998, when dozens died. Fatima said most of the deaths were the result
of people seeking medical treatment too late. The death toll was highest
among the poor, those who were most reluctant to seek medical help, she
said, adding that her office planned to provide free treatment for the poor.
Health officials have also warned of an outbreak in Jakarta this year, with
443 cases but no deaths reported so far. In South Sulawesi dengue fever has
already killed 23 and required 546 others to be admitted to hospital this
year. Besides dengue fever, West Java is facing the similar but non-lethal
chikungunya disease, carried by _Aedes albopictus_ mosquitoes. Chikungunya
follows a 20 year cycle, which explains why most people are unfamiliar with
it. Fatima said the disease had so far affected 400 people in the province.
Its characteristic symptoms include pain in the joints or muscles and
fever. "Chikungunya is relatively [benign], it doesn't lead to death," she
said.
Efforts to fight both diseases are limited to fumigating, which may cause
the mosquitoes to become [resistent] to the chemicals. Health officials
urged the public to drain or cover water where both types of mosquitoes
breed. Health minister Achmad Sujudi has said that his Ministry needed Rp
1.6 trillion (around $180 million) to effectively exterminate the _Aedes
albopictus_ mosquito this year. The budget would cover 70 000 villages
across the country, and also include programs to eradicate other
communicable diseases like dengue fever, leprosy, malaria, and
tuberculosis, officials said.
